content.description: Such cool features on this one. Sit start with LH on left arete, RH on right arete crimps. Scrunchy start.
content.location: Small boulder on the east side of the Cat Daddy boulder.

content.description: Short and powerful. Fun top out
content.location: starts on jugs. Make a long reach with the left hand to a flat edge Sloper.  Then right hand to another decent small flat ish Sloper then Up two more feet to gain a decent holds to pull over  the lip.

content.description:
A sit-start. Begin by grabbing a good sidepull and then reach way up to the lip and struggle to the finish on slopey holds.

Variation - Threshold V4. Again, sit-start and traverse right on pockets until the rock face becomes less-steep and finish the problem by climbing up the face to the top.
content.location: Just to the right of problem 3. Project

content.description: Sit-start and work your way up the face and try to top out on slopey holds.
content.location: This problem can be found on the Northeast corner of the boulder (this is the side of the boulder facing the parking area). At the time of initial development this was the only problem on this side of the boulder, there are likely some others at this time.

content.description: Sit-start and use hard crimping holds, work your way up and try to top out on some terrible slopey holds. Only the hardcore gain the top!
content.location: Just to the right of 7. Project. What's A New Pussycat is the last problem on the Southeast corner of the boulder.

content.description: Project details unknown. If anyone has info on this project please forward it on and I'll update the problem.
content.location: Just to the right of 6. 60% Classic.

content.description: This problem climbs through three of the problems on the face. Starting on the V7/8 what’s a new pussycat. Make two moves with the right hand to gain positive incut them make a big move out left to incut. Then right hand onto the big hold on the lip then continue left topping out 60% classic.
content.location: Start on what’s new pussycat climbing up and left into 60% classic top out

content.description: This is a low traverse starting on 60% classic inn ending what’s new pussycat.
content.location: Sit Starting on 60% classic staying low and traversing to the right into What’s new pussycat.

content.description: Start sitting while matching hands on a jug. From there work your way up the face on thin holds/crimpers. Deadpoint right and the left to top out on some slopey holds.
content.location: Just right of Golden Ladle. Walk-off decent.

content.description:
Sit-start at the base of the boulder where there is an oblong section of lighter colored rock roughly in the middle of the south boulder face. Move up and right, joining problem 6. 60% Classic before topping out on slopey terrain.

This boulder & area was named after this problem.
content.location: As stated in the description, there is section in the middle of the south face that is lighter colored (the guide book describes this as a 'yellow ball of fire'), to the right of problem 4. Project.

content.description: Unknown project, no additional information available at this time. If this is your project let me know the details and I'll update it! Note: unknown rating as well, but MP requires a rating to list the problem so something had to be chosen.
content.location: Starts on the same Southwest corner of the boulder as problems 1 & 2, but heads straight up the arete rather than traversing around to the left.

content.description: Use the same start as problem 1. Low Road (start in big pocket feature on the left side of the steep face).  Instead of staying low on the rock head up a higher line leading to the left to top out.
content.location: Located on the Southwest corner of the boulder. Walk-off decent

content.description: A sit-down start with beginning holds in a big pocket feature on the left side of the steep boulder face. After pulling up off the ground negotiate a low traverse around the left side of the rock and up to a slopey top out.
content.protection: Good landings and areas to place a crash-pad.
content.location: Located on the Southwest corner of the boulder. Walk-off decent.
